    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <persName ref="pe0327">Robson</persName> has layed by for you a large paper copy of my 
                    <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0022">arctic Zoology</title>
                    </bibl>: <note type="editorial">[PROBLEMATIC: SEE WORKS LIST. I think this may refer to the 'Introduction of the Arctic World', 1784; but date would still be a problem.]</note>
                    but is at a loss about the conveyance. Please to inform me &amp; He shall obey <choice>
                        <abbr>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <expan>your</expan>
                    </choice>
                    orders. I am already busied in enriching <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0027">my own copy</title>
                    </bibl>.
                    one means is by buying a most neat pyrated edition of book in <choice>
                        <abbr>oct<hi rend="superscript">vo</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <expan>octavo</expan>
                    </choice>
                    1.5.0. &amp; inserting in it the prints relative to the subject. if you chuse it I will send you a copy or do any other Commission which you may have forgot.
                    <persName ref="pe0474">A young man</persName> is now copying most picturesque <rs type="art" ref="ardb.xml#ar0049">views in <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl1014">nova scotia</placeName>
                    </rs>
                    for the purpose of illustration if you wish it, He may Copy some from mine. <note type="editorial">Views in Nova Scotia (frequently mentioned in Arctic Zoology) and young man copying views not identified. If we could find Pennant's extra-illustrated Arctic zoology, this problem would be at least partially solved. LINK TO WORKS LIST: Arctic zoology: Pennant's copy [PROBLEMATIC, AS ABOVE]</note> he is reasonable.</p>
                <p>I hope you enjoy sunshine &amp; warm banks. we are chilled between the walls of <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0699">this city</placeName>: but my amusements congenial with yours keeps my blood in motion.</p>
                <p>I beg you would present my best <choice>
                        <abbr>complim<hi rend="superscript">ts</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <expan>compliments</expan>
                    </choice> to <persName ref="pe0331 pe0336">miss Bulls</persName> &amp; </p>
                <closer>think me Dear Sir
                    <lb/>Most truely <choice>
                        <abbr>y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <expan>yours</expan>
                    </choice>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">
                            <choice>
                                <abbr>Tho.</abbr>
                                <expan>Thomas</expan>
                            </choice> Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0753">Upper Brook Street</placeName> March 9<hi rend="supercsript">th</hi> 1783.</dateline>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>I continue here till the 10<hi rend="supercsript">th</hi>.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p>
                    <stamp type="postmark">9 MR</stamp>
                    <address>
                    <addrLine>To <persName ref="pe0313">Richard Bull <choice>
                                    <abbr>Esq<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                                    </abbr>
                                    <expan>Esquire</expan>
                                </choice>
                            </persName> | at <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl1013">Northcot House | Isle of Wight</placeName>
                            <note type="editorial">After 1783, Richard Bull began using North Court, in the parish of Shorwell on the Isle of Wight, as his country residence, purchasing the property in 1795. Evans, 'Richard Bull and Thomas Pennant'</note>
                        </addrLine>
                        <addrLine/>
                    </address>
                </p>
            </div>
